# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: csp-hardening
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] This article brings forth a way to integrate the **defense in depth** concept to the client-side of web applications.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] By injecting the Content-Security-Policy (CSP) headers from the server, the browser is aware and capable of protecting the user from dynamic calls that will load content into the page currently being visited.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] The increase in XSS (Cross-Site Scripting), clickjacking, and cross-site leak vulnerabilities demands a more **defense in depth** security approach.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] By restricting where HTML forms on your website can submit their data, injecting phishing forms won't work either.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] And by restricting the HTML object tag, it also won't be possible for an attacker to inject malicious flash/Java/other legacy executables on the page.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Attacks like clickjacking and some variants of browser side-channel attacks (xs-leaks) require a malicious website to load the target website in a frame.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Historically the `X-Frame-Options` header has been used for this, but it has been obsoleted by the `frame-ancestors` CSP directive.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] A strong CSP provides an effective **second layer** of protection against various types of vulnerabilities, especially XSS.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Although CSP doesn't prevent web applications from *containing* vulnerabilities, it can make those vulnerabilities significantly more difficult for an attacker to exploit.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Even on a fully static website, which does not accept any user input, a CSP can be used to enforce the use of Subresource Integrity (SRI).
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] This can help prevent malicious code from being loaded on the website if one of the third-party sites hosting JavaScript files (such as analytics scripts) is compromised.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] With all that being said, CSP **should not** be relied upon as the only defensive mechanism against XSS.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] You must still follow good development practices such as the ones described in Cross-Site Scripting Prevention Cheat Sheet, and then deploy CSP on top of that as a bonus security layer.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] You can deliver a Content Security Policy to your website in three ways.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Send a Content-Security-Policy HTTP response header from your web server.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Using a header is the preferred way and supports the full CSP feature set.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Send it in all HTTP responses, not just the index page.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Using the `Content-Security-Policy-Report-Only`, you can deliver a CSP that doesn't get enforced.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Still, violation reports are printed to the console and delivered to a violation endpoint if the `report-to` and `report-uri` directives are used.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] This is also a W3C Spec standard header.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Supported by Firefox 23+, Chrome 25+ and Opera 19+, whereby the policy is non-blocking ("fail open") and a report is sent to the URL designated by the `report-uri` (or newer `report-to`) directive.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Browsers fully support the ability of a site to use both `Content-Security-Policy` and `Content-Security-Policy-Report-Only` together, without any issues.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] This pattern can be used for example to run a strict `Report-Only` policy (to get many violation reports), while having a looser enforced policy (to avoid breaking legitimate site functionality).
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Sometimes you cannot use the Content-Security-Policy header if you are, e.g., Deploying your HTML files in a CDN where the headers are out of your control.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Almost everything is still supported, including full XSS defenses.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] However, you will not be able to use framing protections, sandboxing, or a CSP violation logging endpoint.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] The original mechanism for building a CSP involved creating allow-lists which would define the content and sources that were permitted in the context of the HTML page.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] However, current leading practice is to create a "Strict" CSP which is much easier to deploy and more secure as it is less likely to be bypassed.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] The `strict-dynamic` directive can optionally also be used to make it easier to implement a Strict CSP.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] When inline scripts are required, the `script-src 'hash_algo-hash'` is another option for allowing only specific scripts to execute.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] This is a great example of using hashes.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] If you change *anything* inside the script tag (even whitespace) by, e.g., formatting your code, the hash will be different, and the script won't render.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] The `strict-dynamic` directive can be used as part of a Strict CSP in combination with either hashes or nonces.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] If a script block which has either the correct hash or nonce is creating additional DOM elements and executing JS inside of them, `strict-dynamic` tells the browser to trust those elements as well without having to explicitly add nonces or hashes for each one.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Note that whilst `strict-dynamic` is a CSP level 3 feature, CSP level 3 is very widely supported in common, modern browsers.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] For more details, check out strict-dynamic usage.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Multiple types of directives exist that allow the developer to control the flow of the policies granularly.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Note that creating a non-Strict policy that is too granular or permissive is likely to lead to bypasses and a loss of protection.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Fetch directives tell the browser the locations to trust and load resources from.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Most fetch directives have a certain fallback list specified in w3.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] This list allows for granular control of the source of scripts, images, files, etc.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Document directives instruct the browser about the properties of the document to which the policies will apply to.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Navigation directives instruct the browser about the locations that the document can navigate to or be embedded from.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Reporting directives deliver violations of prevented behaviors to specified locations.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] These directives serve no purpose on their own and are dependent on other directives.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] For backward compatibility, declare both directives in conjunction.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Browsers that support `report-to` will use it and ignore `report-uri`; older browsers fall back to `report-uri`.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] Once support for legacy browsers is no longer required, `report-uri` can be removed.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] To better understand how the directive sources work, check out the source lists from w3c.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] A strict policy's role is to protect against classical stored, reflected, and some of the DOM XSS attacks and should be the optimal goal of any team trying to implement CSP.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] As noted above, Google went ahead and set up a detailed and methodological instructions for creating a Strict CSP.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] This policy can be used if it is not possible to create a Strict Policy and it prevents cross-site framing and cross-site form-submissions.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] It will only allow resources from the originating domain for all the default level directives and will not allow inline scripts/styles to execute.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] If your application functions with these restrictions, it drastically reduces your attack surface and works with most modern browsers.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] This policy allows images, scripts, AJAX, and CSS from the same origin and does not allow any other resources to load (e.g., object, frame, media, etc.).
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy-cheat-sheet] With `app.js` containing the `var foo = "314"` code.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] The standard, originally named Content Restrictions, was proposed by Robert Hansen in 2004, first implemented in Firefox 4 and quickly picked up by other browsers.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] Version 1 of the standard was published in 2012 as W3C candidate recommendation and quickly with further versions (Level 2) published in 2014.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] As of 2023, the draft of Level 3 is being developed with the new features being quickly adopted by the web browsers.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] A website can declare multiple CSP headers, also mixing enforcement and report-only ones.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] Each header will be processed separately by the browser.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] CSP can also be delivered within the HTML code using a meta tag, although in this case its effectiveness will be limited.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] Internet Explorer 10 and Internet Explorer 11 also support CSP, but only sandbox directive, using the experimental `X-Content-Security-Policy` header.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] A number of web application frameworks support CSP, for example AngularJS (natively) and Django (middleware).
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] Instructions for Ruby on Rails have been posted by GitHub.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] Web framework support is however only required if the CSP contents somehow depend on the web application's state—such as usage of the `nonce` origin.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] Otherwise, the CSP is rather static and can be delivered from web application tiers above the application, for example on load balancer or web server.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] In December 2015 and December 2016, a few methods of bypassing `'nonce'` allowlisting origins were published.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] In January 2016, another method was published, which leverages server-wide CSP allowlisting to exploit old and vulnerable versions of JavaScript libraries hosted at the same server (frequent case with CDN servers).
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] In May 2017 one more method was published to bypass CSP using web application frameworks code.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] If the `Content-Security-Policy` header is present in the server response, a compliant client enforces the declarative allowlist policy.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] One example goal of a policy is a stricter execution mode for JavaScript in order to prevent certain cross-site scripting attacks.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] While using CSP in a new application may be quite straightforward, especially with CSP-compatible JavaScript framework, existing applications may require some refactoring—or relaxing the policy.
[src:csp-hardening/content-security-policy] Recommended coding practice for CSP-compatible web applications is to load code from external source files (`<script src>`), parse JSON instead of evaluating it and use `EventTarget.addEventListener()` to set event handlers.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] OWASP considers the term cross-site scripting to be a misnomer.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] It initially was an attack that was used for breaching data across sites, but gradually started to include other forms of data injection attacks.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Security on the web depends on a variety of mechanisms, including an underlying concept of trust known as the same-origin policy.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Content from URLs where any of these three attributes are different will have to be granted permissions separately.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting attacks use known vulnerabilities in web-based applications, their servers, or the plug-in systems on which they rely.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Exploiting one of these, attackers fold malicious content into the content being delivered from the compromised site.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] When the resulting combined content arrives at the client-side web browser, it has all been delivered from the trusted source, and thus operates under the permissions granted to that system.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] By finding ways of injecting malicious scripts into web pages, an attacker can gain elevated access-privileges to sensitive page content, to session cookies, and to a variety of other information maintained by the browser on behalf of the user.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting attacks are a case of code injection.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Microsoft security-engineers introduced the term "cross-site scripting" in January 2000.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] The definition gradually expanded to encompass other modes of code injection, including persistent and non-JavaScript vectors (including ActiveX, Java, VBScript, Flash, or even HTML scripts), causing some confusion to newcomers to the field of information security.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] XSS vulnerabilities have been reported and exploited since the 1990s.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Prominent sites affected in the past include the social-networking sites Twitter and Facebook.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting flaws have since surpassed buffer overflows to become the most common publicly reported security vulnerability, with some researchers in 2007 estimating as many as 68% of websites are likely open to XSS attacks.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] There is no single, standardized classification of cross-site scripting flaws, but most experts distinguish between at least two primary flavors of XSS flaws: *non-persistent* and *persistent*.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Some sources further divide these two groups into *traditional* (caused by server-side code flaws) and *DOM-based* (in client-side code).
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] The *non-persistent* (or *reflected*) cross-site scripting vulnerability is by far the most basic type of web vulnerability.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] These holes show up when the data provided by a web client, most commonly in HTTP query parameters (e.g.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] HTML form submission), is used immediately by server-side scripts to parse and display a page of results for that user, without properly sanitizing the content.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Because HTML documents have a flat, serial structure that mixes control statements, formatting, and the actual content, any non-validated user-supplied data included in the resulting page without proper HTML encoding, may lead to markup injection.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] A classic example of a potential vector is a site search engine: if one searches for a string, the search string will typically be redisplayed verbatim on the result page to indicate what was searched for.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] If this response does not properly escape or reject HTML control characters, a cross-site scripting flaw will ensue.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] A reflected attack is typically delivered via email or a neutral web site.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] The bait is an innocent-looking URL, pointing to a trusted site but containing the XSS vector.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] If the trusted site is vulnerable to the vector, clicking the link can cause the victim's browser to execute the injected script.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] A classic example of this is with online message boards where users are allowed to post HTML formatted messages for other users to read.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] For example, suppose there is a dating website where members scan the profiles of other members to see if they look interesting.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] For privacy reasons, this site hides everybody's real name and email.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] The only time a member's real name and email are in the browser is when the member is signed in, and they can't see anyone else's.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Suppose that Mallory, an attacker, joins the site and wants to figure out the real names of the people she sees on the site.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] To do so, she writes a script designed to run from other users' browsers when *they* visit *her* profile.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] The script then sends a quick message to her own server, which collects this information.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] To do this, for the question "Describe your Ideal First Date", Mallory gives a short answer (to appear normal), but the text at the end of her answer is her script to steal names and emails.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] If the script is enclosed inside a `<script>` element, it won't be shown on the screen.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Then suppose that Bob, a member of the dating site, reaches Mallory's profile, which has her answer to the First Date question.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Her script is run automatically by the browser and steals a copy of Bob's real name and email directly from his own machine.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Persistent XSS vulnerabilities can be more significant than other types because an attacker's malicious script is rendered automatically, without the need to individually target victims or lure them to a third-party website.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Particularly in the case of social networking sites, the code would be further designed to self-propagate across accounts, creating a type of client-side worm.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] The methods of injection can vary a great deal; in some cases, the attacker may not even need to directly interact with the web functionality itself to exploit such a hole.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Any data received by the web application (via email, system logs, IM etc.) that can be controlled by an attacker could become an injection vector.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] XSS vulnerabilities were originally found in applications that performed all data processing on the server side.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] User input (including an XSS vector) would be sent to the server, and then sent back to the user as a web page.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] The need for an improved user experience resulted in popularity of applications that had a majority of the presentation logic (maybe written in JavaScript) working on the client-side that pulled data, on-demand, from the server using AJAX.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] As the JavaScript code was also processing user input and rendering it in the web page content, a new sub-class of reflected XSS attacks started to appear that was called *DOM-based cross-site scripting*.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] In a DOM-based XSS attack, the malicious data does not touch the web server.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Rather, it is being reflected by the JavaScript code, fully on the client side.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] An example of a DOM-based XSS vulnerability is the bug found in 2011 in a number of jQuery plugins.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Prevention strategies for DOM-based XSS attacks include very similar measures to traditional XSS prevention strategies but implemented in JavaScript code and contained in web pages (i.e. input validation and escaping).
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Some JavaScript frameworks have built-in countermeasures against this and other types of attack — for example AngularJS.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Self-XSS is a form of XSS vulnerability that relies on social engineering in order to trick the victim into executing malicious JavaScript code in their browser.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Although it is technically not a true XSS vulnerability due to the fact it relies on socially engineering a user into executing code rather than a flaw in the affected website allowing an attacker to do so, it still poses the same risks as a regular XSS vulnerability if properly executed.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Mutated XSS happens when the attacker injects something that is seemingly safe but is rewritten and modified by the browser while parsing the markup.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] This makes it extremely hard to detect or sanitize within the website's application logic.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] An example is rebalancing unclosed quotation marks or even adding quotation marks to unquoted values in CSS font-family properties.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] There are several escaping schemes that can be used depending on where the untrusted string needs to be placed within an HTML document including HTML entity encoding, JavaScript escaping, CSS escaping, and URL (or percent) encoding.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Most web applications that do not need to accept rich data can use escaping to largely eliminate the risk of XSS attacks in a fairly straightforward manner.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Performing HTML entity encoding only on the five XML significant characters is not always sufficient to prevent many forms of XSS attacks, security encoding libraries are usually easier to use.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Some web template systems understand the structure of the HTML they produce and automatically pick an appropriate encoder.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Many operators of particular web applications (e.g. forums and webmail) allow users to utilize HTML markup.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] When accepting HTML input from users (say, `<b>very</b> large`), output encoding (such as `&lt;b&gt;very&lt;/b&gt; large`) will not suffice since the user input needs to be rendered as HTML by the browser (so it shows as `**very** large`, instead of `<b>very</b> large`).
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Stopping an XSS attack when accepting HTML input from users is much more complex in this situation.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Often, untrusted HTML input must be run through an HTML sanitization engine to ensure that it does not contain potentially malicious JavaScript code.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Many validations rely on parsing out (blacklisting) specific "at risk" HTML tags such as the `<iframe>`, `<link>`, and `<script>` tag, or by only allowing certain tags and removing or escaping others.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Another popular method is to strip user input of " and ' however this can also be bypassed as the payload can be concealed with obfuscation.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Besides content filtering, other imperfect methods for cross-site scripting mitigation are also commonly used.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] One example is the use of additional security controls when handling cookie-based user authentication.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Many web applications rely on session cookies for authentication between individual HTTP requests, and because client-side scripts generally have access to these cookies, simple XSS exploits can steal these cookies.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] To mitigate this particular threat (though not the XSS problem in general), many web applications tie session cookies to the IP address of the user who originally logged in, then only permit that IP to use that cookie.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] This is effective in most situations (if an attacker is only after the cookie), but obviously breaks down in situations where an attacker is behind the same NATed IP address or web proxy as the victim, or the victim is changing his or her mobile IP.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Another mitigation present in Internet Explorer (since version 6), Firefox (since version 2.0.0.5), Safari (since version 4), Opera (since version 9.5) and Google Chrome, is an *HttpOnly* flag which allows a web server to set a cookie that is unavailable to client-side scripts.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] While beneficial, the feature can neither fully prevent cookie theft nor prevent attacks within the browser.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] While Web 2.0 and Ajax developers require the use of JavaScript, some web applications are written to allow operation without the need for any client-side scripts.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] This allows users, if they choose, to disable scripting in their browsers before using the application.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] In this way, even potentially malicious client-side scripts could be inserted unescaped on a page, and users would not be susceptible to XSS attacks.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Some browsers or browser plugins can be configured to disable client-side scripts on a per-domain basis.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] This approach is of limited value if scripting is allowed by default, since it blocks bad sites only *after* the user knows that they are bad, which is too late.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Functionality that blocks all scripting and external inclusions by default and then allows the user to enable it on a per-domain basis is more effective.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] This has been possible for a long time in Internet Explorer (since version 4) by setting up its so called "Security Zones", and in Opera (since version 9) using its "Site Specific Preferences".
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] A solution for Firefox and other Gecko-based browsers is the open source NoScript add-on which, in addition to the ability to enable scripts on a per-domain basis, provides some XSS protection even when scripts are enabled.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Another problem with script blocking is that many users do not understand it, and do not know how to properly secure their browsers.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Yet another drawback is that many sites do not work without client-side scripting, forcing users to disable protection for that site and opening their systems to vulnerabilities.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] The Firefox NoScript extension enables users to allow scripts selectively from a given page while disallowing others on the same page.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] For example, scripts from example.com could be allowed, while scripts from advertisingagency.com that are attempting to run on the same page could be disallowed.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Trusted types changes Web APIs to check that values have been trademarked as trusted.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] As long as programs only trademark trustworthy values, an attacker who controls a JavaScript string value cannot cause XSS.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Trusted types are designed to be auditable by blue teams.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] Another defense approach is to use automated tools that will remove XSS malicious code in web pages, these tools use static analysis and/or pattern matching methods to identify malicious codes potentially and secure them using methods like escaping.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] When a cookie is set with the `SameSite=Strict` parameter, it is stripped from all cross-origin requests.
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] When set with `SameSite=Lax`, it is stripped from all non-"safe" cross-origin requests (that is, requests other than GET, OPTIONS, and TRACE which have read-only semantics).
[src:csp-hardening/cross-site-scripting] The feature is implemented in Google Chrome since version 63 and Firefox since version 60.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] In cryptography, a **nonce** is an arbitrary number that can be used just once in a cryptographic communication.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] It is often a random or pseudo-random number issued in an authentication protocol to ensure that each communication session is unique, and therefore that old communications cannot be reused in replay attacks.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] Nonces can also be useful as initialization vectors and in cryptographic hash functions.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] A nonce is an arbitrary number used only once in a cryptographic communication, in the spirit of a nonce word.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] They are often random or pseudo-random numbers.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] Many nonces also include a timestamp to ensure exact timeliness, though this requires clock synchronisation between organisations.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] The addition of a client nonce ("**cnonce**") helps to improve the security in some ways as implemented in digest access authentication.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] To ensure that a nonce is used only once, it should be time-variant (including a suitably fine-grained timestamp in its value), or generated with enough random bits to ensure an insignificantly low chance of repeating a previously generated value.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] Some authors define pseudo-randomness (or unpredictability) as a requirement for a nonce.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] Nonce is a word dating back to Middle English for something only used once or temporarily (often with the construction "for the nonce").
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] It descends from the construction "then anes" ("the one [purpose]").
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] A false etymology claiming it to stand for "number used once" or similar is incorrect.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] Authentication protocols may use nonces to ensure that old communications cannot be reused in replay attacks.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] For instance, nonces are used in HTTP digest access authentication to calculate an MD5 digest of the password.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] The nonces are different each time the 401 authentication challenge response code is presented, thus making replay attacks virtually impossible.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] The scenario of ordering products over the Internet can provide an example of the usefulness of nonces in replay attacks.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] An attacker could take the encrypted information and—without needing to decrypt—could continue to send a particular order to the supplier, thereby ordering products over and over again under the same name and purchase information.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] The nonce is used to give 'originality' to a given message so that if the company receives any other orders from the same person with the same nonce, it will discard those as invalid orders.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] A nonce may be used to ensure security for a stream cipher.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] Where the same key is used for more than one message and then a different nonce is used to ensure that the keystream is different for different messages encrypted with that key; often the message number is used.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] Secret nonce values are used by the Lamport signature scheme as a signer-side secret which can be selectively revealed for comparison to public hashes for signature creation and verification.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] Nonces are used in proof-of-work systems to vary the input to a cryptographic hash function so as to obtain a hash for a certain input that fulfils certain arbitrary conditions.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] In doing so, it becomes far more difficult to create a "desirable" hash than to verify it, shifting the burden of work onto one side of a transaction or system.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] Similarly, the Bitcoin blockchain hashing algorithm can be tuned to an arbitrary difficulty by changing the required minimum/maximum value of the hash so that the number of bitcoins awarded for new blocks does not increase linearly with increased network computation power as new users join.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] This is likewise achieved by forcing Bitcoin miners to add nonce values to the value being hashed to change the hash algorithm output.
[src:csp-hardening/cryptographic-nonce] As cryptographic hash algorithms cannot easily be predicted based on their inputs, this makes the act of blockchain hashing and the possibility of being awarded bitcoins something of a lottery, where the first "miner" to find a nonce that delivers a desirable hash is awarded bitcoins.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In some programming languages, **`eval`**, short for evaluate, is a function which evaluates a string as though it were an expression in the language, and returns a result; in others, it executes multiple lines of code as though they had been included instead of the line including the `eval`.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The input to `eval` is not necessarily a string; it may be structured representation of code, such as an abstract syntax tree (like Lisp forms), or of special type such as `code` (as in Python).
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The analog for a statement is exec, which executes a string (or code in other format) as if it were a statement; in some languages, such as Python, both are present, while in other languages only one of either `eval` or `exec` is.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Using `eval` with data from an untrusted source may introduce security vulnerabilities.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] An attacker could supply the program with the string `"session.update(authenticated=True)"` as data, which would update the `session` dictionary to set an authenticated key to be True.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] To remedy this, all data which will be used with `eval` must be escaped, or it must be run without access to potentially harmful functions.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In interpreted languages, `eval` is almost always implemented with the same interpreter as normal code.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In compiled languages, the same compiler used to compile programs may be embedded in programs using the `eval` function; separate interpreters are sometimes used, though this results in code duplication.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In JavaScript, `eval` is something of a hybrid between an expression evaluator and a statement executor.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] It returns the result of the last expression evaluated.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] One use of JavaScript's `eval` is to parse JSON text, perhaps as part of an Ajax framework.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] However, modern browsers provide `JSON.parse` as a more secure alternative for this task.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In ActionScript (Flash's programming language), `eval` cannot be used to evaluate arbitrary expressions.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] According to the Flash 8 documentation, its usage is limited to expressions which represent "the name of a variable, property, object, or movie clip to retrieve.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The ActionScript 3 Eval Library and the D.eval API were development projects to create equivalents to `eval` in ActionScript 3.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Both have ended, as Adobe Flash Player has reached its end-of-life.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Lisp was the original language to make use of an `eval` function in 1958.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In fact, definition of the `eval` function led to the first implementation of the language interpreter.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Before the `eval` function was defined, Lisp functions were manually compiled to assembly language statements.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] However, once the `eval` function had been manually compiled it was then used as part of a simple read–eval–print loop which formed the basis of the first Lisp interpreter.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Later versions of the Lisp `eval` function have also been implemented as compilers.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The `eval` function in Lisp expects a form to be evaluated as its argument.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The resulting value of the given form will be the returned value of the call to `eval`.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Lisp is well known to be very flexible and so is the `eval` function.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] One major point of confusion is the question, in which context the symbols in the form will be evaluated.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In the above example, `form1` contains the symbol `+`.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Evaluation of this symbol must yield the function for addition to make the example work as intended.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Thus some dialects of Lisp allow an additional parameter for `eval` to specify the context of evaluation (similar to the optional arguments to Python's `eval` function - see below).
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In Perl, the `eval` function is something of a hybrid between an expression evaluator and a statement executor.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] It returns the result of the last expression evaluated (all statements are expressions in Perl programming), and allows the final semicolon to be left off.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Perl also has `eval` *blocks*, which serves as its exception handling mechanism (see Exception handling syntax#Perl).
[src:csp-hardening/eval] This differs from the above use of `eval` with strings in that code inside `eval` blocks is interpreted at compile-time instead of run-time, so it is not the meaning of `eval` used in this article.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In PHP, `eval` executes code in a string almost exactly as if it had been put in the file instead of the call to `eval()`.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The only exception is that errors are reported as coming from a call to `eval()`, and return statements become the result of the function.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Unlike some languages, the argument to `eval` must be a string of one or more complete statements, not just expressions; however, one can get the "expression" form of `eval` by putting the expression in a return statement, which causes `eval` to return the result of that expression.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Unlike some languages, PHP's `eval` is a "language construct" rather than a function, and so cannot be used in some contexts where functions can be, like higher-order functions.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In Lua 5.1, `loadstring` compiles Lua code into an anonymous function.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Lua 5.2 deprecates `loadstring` in favor of the existing `load` function, which has been augmented to accept strings.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In addition, it allows providing the function's environment directly, as environments are now upvalues.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] PostScript's `exec` operator takes an operand — if it is a simple literal it pushes it back on the stack.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] which pops the string "Hello World" off the stack and displays it on the screen, to have an executable type, then is executed.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] PostScript's `run` operator is similar in functionality but instead the interpreter interprets PostScript expressions in a file, itself.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In Python, the `eval` function in its simplest form evaluates a single expression.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The `eval` function takes two optional arguments, `global` and `locals`, which allow the programmer to set up a restricted environment for the evaluation of the expression.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The most general form for evaluating statements/expressions is using code objects.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] D is a statically compiled language and therefore does not include an "`eval`" statement in the traditional sense, but does include the related "`mixin`" statement.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The difference is that, where "`eval`" interprets a string as code at runtime, with a "`mixin`" the string is statically compiled like ordinary code and must be known at compile time.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The above example will compile to exactly the same assembly language instructions as if "`num++;`" had been written directly instead of mixed in.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The argument to mixin doesn't need to be a string literal, but arbitrary expressions resulting in a string value, including function calls, that can be evaluated at compile time.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] ColdFusion's `evaluate` function lets users evaluate a string expression at runtime.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] It is particularly useful when users need to programmatically choose the variable they want to read from.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The Ruby programming language interpreter offers an `eval` function similar to Python or Perl, and also allows a scope, or binding, to be specified.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Aside from specifying a function's binding, `eval` may also be used to evaluate an expression within a specific class definition binding or object instance binding, allowing classes to be extended with new methods specified in strings.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Most standard implementations of Forth have two variants of `eval`: `EVALUATE` and `INTERPRET`.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In REALbasic, there is a class called RBScript which can execute REALbasic code at runtime.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] RBScript is very sandboxed—only the most core language features are there, and users have to allow it access to things they would like it to have.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] They can optionally assign an object to the context property.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] This allows for the code in RBScript to call functions and use properties of the context object.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] However, it is still limited to only understanding the most basic types, so if they have a function that returns a Dictionary or MySpiffyObject, RBScript will be unable to use it.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Users can also communicate with their RBScript through the Print and Input events.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Microsoft's VBScript, which is an interpreted language, has two constructs.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] `Eval` is a function evaluator that can include calls to user-defined functions.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] (These functions may have side-effects such as changing the values of global variables.) `Execute` executes one or more colon-separated statements, which can change global state.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Both VBScript and JScript `eval` are available to developers of compiled Windows applications (written in languages which do not support Eval) through an ActiveX control called the Microsoft Script Control, whose Eval method can be called by application code.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] To support calling of user-defined functions, one must first initialize the control with the AddCode method, which loads a string (or a string resource) containing a library of user-defined functions defined in the language of one's choice, prior to calling Eval.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Visual Basic for Applications (VBA), the programming language of Microsoft Office, is a virtual machine language where the runtime environment compiles and runs p-code.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Its flavor of Eval supports only expression evaluation, where the expression may include user-defined functions and objects (but not user-defined variable names).
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Of note, the evaluator is different from VBS, and invocation of certain user-defined functions may work differently in VBA than the identical code in VBScript.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] As Smalltalk's compiler classes are part of the standard class library and usually present at run time, these can be used to evaluate a code string.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The Tcl programming language has a command called `eval`, which executes the source code provided as an argument.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Tcl represents all source code as strings, with curly braces acting as quotation marks, so that the argument to `eval` can have the same formatting as any other source code.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] bs has an `eval` function that takes one string argument.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The function is both an expression evaluator and a statement executor.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In the latter role, it can also be used for error handling.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The following examples and text are from the `bs` man page as appears in the UNIX System V Release 3.2 Programmer's Manual.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The *eval* command is present in all Unix shells, including the original "sh" (Bourne shell).
[src:csp-hardening/eval] It concatenates all the arguments with spaces, then re-parses and executes the result as a command.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In PowerShell, the `Invoke-Expression` Cmdlet serves the same purpose as the eval function in programming languages like JavaScript, PHP and Python.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The Cmdlet runs any PowerShell expression that is provided as a command parameter in the form of a string and outputs the result of the specified expression.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Usually, the output of the Cmdlet is of the same type as the result of executing the expression.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] However, if the result is an empty array, it outputs `$null`.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In case the result is a single-element array, it outputs that single element.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Similar to JavaScript, PowerShell allows the final semicolon to be left off.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In 1966 IBM Conversational Programming System (CPS) introduced a microprogrammed function `EVAL` to perform "interpretive evaluation of expressions which are written in a modified Polish-string notation" on an IBM System/360 Model 50.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Microcoding this function was "substantially more" than five times faster compared to a program that interpreted an assignment statement.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In theoretical computer science, a careful distinction is commonly made between eval and apply.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] *Eval* is understood to be the step of converting a quoted string into a callable function and its arguments, whereas *apply* is the actual call of the function with a given set of arguments.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] The distinction is particularly noticeable in functional languages, and languages based on lambda calculus, such as LISP and Scheme.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] where the function *f* is to be called with argument *x*.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] In category theory, the *eval* morphism is used to define the closed monoidal category.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Thus, for example, the category of sets, with functions taken as morphisms, and the cartesian product taken as the product, forms a Cartesian closed category.
[src:csp-hardening/eval] Here, *eval* (or, properly speaking, *apply*) together with its right adjoint, currying, form the simply typed lambda calculus, which can be interpreted to be the morphisms of Cartesian closed categories.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] In computing, the **same-origin policy** (**SOP**) is a concept in the web application security model.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Under the policy, a web browser permits scripts contained in a first web page to access data in a second web page, but only if both web pages have the same *origin*.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] An origin is defined as a combination of URI scheme, host name, and port number.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] This policy prevents a malicious script on one page from obtaining access to sensitive data on another web page through that page's Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] This mechanism bears a particular significance for modern web applications that extensively depend on HTTPS cookies to maintain authenticated user sessions, as servers act based on the HTTP cookie information to reveal sensitive information or perform state-changing actions.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] A strict separation between content provided by unrelated sites must be maintained on the client-side to prevent the loss of data confidentiality or integrity.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy applies only to scripts.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] This means that resources such as images, CSS, and dynamically loaded scripts can be accessed across origins via the corresponding HTML tags (with fonts being a notable exception).
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Attacks take advantage of the fact that the same origin policy does not apply to HTML tags.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] There are some mechanisms available to relax the SOP; one of them is cross-origin resource sharing (CORS).
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] The concept of same-origin policy was introduced by Netscape Navigator 2.02 in 1995, shortly after the introduction of JavaScript in Netscape 2.0.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] JavaScript enabled scripting on web pages, and in particular programmatic access to the DOM.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] The policy was originally designed to protect access to the DOM, but has since been broadened to protect sensitive parts of the global JavaScript object.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] All modern browsers implement some form of the same-origin policy as it is an important security cornerstone.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] The algorithm used to calculate the "origin" of a URI is specified in RFC 6454, Section 4.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] For absolute URIs, the origin is the triple {scheme, host, port}.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] If the URI does not use a hierarchical element as a naming authority (see RFC 3986, Section 3.2) or if the URI is not an absolute URI, then a globally unique identifier is used.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Two resources are considered to be of the same origin if and only if all these values are exactly the same.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] To illustrate, the following table gives an overview of typical outcomes for checks against the URL "**http://www.example.com/dir/page.html**".
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Unlike other browsers, Internet Explorer does not include the port in the calculation of the origin, using the Security Zone in its place.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy protects against reusing authenticated sessions across origins.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] The following example illustrates a potential security risk that could arise without the same-origin policy.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Assume that a user is visiting a banking website and doesn't log out.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Then, the user goes to another site that has malicious JavaScript code that requests data from the banking site.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Because the user is still logged in on the banking site, the malicious code could do anything the user could do on the banking site.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] For example, it could get a list of the user's last transactions, create a new transaction, etc.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] This is because, in the original spirit of a World Wide Web, browsers are required to tag along authentication details such as session cookies and platform-level kinds of the Authorization request header to the banking site based on the domain of the banking site.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] The bank site owners would expect that regular browsers of users visiting the malicious site do not allow the code loaded from the malicious site access the banking session cookie or platform-level authorization.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] While it is true that JavaScript has no direct access to the banking session cookie, it could still send and receive requests to the banking site with the banking site's session cookie.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Same Origin Policy was introduced as a requirement for security-minded browsers to deny read access to responses from across origins, with the assumption that the majority of users choose to use compliant browsers.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Counteracting the abuse of the write permission requires additional CSRF protections by the target sites.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] In some circumstances, the same-origin policy is too restrictive, posing problems for large websites that use multiple subdomains.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] At first, a number of workarounds such as using the fragment identifier or the `window.name` property were used to pass data between documents residing in different domains.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Netscape Navigator briefly contained a taint checking feature.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] The feature was experimentally introduced in 1997 as part of Netscape 3.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] The feature was turned off by default, but if enabled by a user it would allow websites to attempt to read JavaScript properties of windows and frames belonging to a different domain.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] The browser would then ask the user whether to permit the access in question.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] If two windows (or frames) contain scripts that set domain to the same value, the same-origin policy is relaxed for these two windows, and each window can interact with the other.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] For example, cooperating scripts in documents loaded from orders.example.com and catalog.example.com might set their `document.domain` properties to “example.com”, thereby making the documents appear to have the same origin and enabling each document to read properties of the other.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Setting this property implicitly sets the port to null, which most browsers will interpret differently from port 80 or even an unspecified port.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] To assure that access will be allowed by the browser, set the document.domain property of both pages.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] The `document.domain` concept was introduced as part of Netscape Navigator 3, released in 1996.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] The other technique for relaxing the same-origin policy is standardized under the name cross-origin resource sharing (CORS).
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] This standard extends HTTP with a new `Origin` request header and a new `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` response header.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] It allows servers to use a header to explicitly list origins that may request a file or to use a wildcard and allow a file to be requested by any site.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Browsers such as Firefox 3.5, Safari 4 and Internet Explorer 10 use this header to allow the cross-origin HTTP requests with XMLHttpRequest that would otherwise have been forbidden by the same-origin policy.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Another technique, cross-document messaging, allows a script from one page to pass textual messages to a script on another page regardless of the script origins.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Calling the postMessage() method on a Window object asynchronously fires an "onmessage" event in that window, triggering any user-defined event handlers.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] A script in one page still cannot directly access methods or variables in the other page, but they can communicate safely through this message-passing technique.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Since HTML `<script>` elements are allowed to retrieve and execute content from other domains, a page can bypass the same-origin policy and receive JSON data from a different domain by loading a resource that returns a JSONP payload.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] JSONP payloads consist of an internal JSON payload wrapped by a pre-defined function call.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] When the script resource is loaded by the browser, the designated callback function will be invoked to process the wrapped JSON payload.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Modern browsers will permit a script to connect to a WebSocket address without applying the same-origin policy.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] However, they recognize when a WebSocket URI is used, and insert an **Origin:** header into the request that indicates the origin of the script requesting the connection.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] To ensure cross-site security, the WebSocket server must verify that that origin is permitted to receive a reply.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] The behavior of same-origin checks and related mechanisms is not well-defined in a number of corner cases such as for pseudo-protocols that do not have a clearly defined host name or port associated with their URLs (file:, data:, etc.).
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] This historically caused a fair number of security problems, such as the generally undesirable ability of any locally stored HTML file to access all other files on the disk, or communicate with any site on the Internet.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Lastly, certain types of attacks, such as DNS rebinding or server-side proxies, permit the host name check to be partly subverted, and make it possible for rogue web pages to directly interact with sites through addresses other than their "true", canonical origin.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] The impact of such attacks is limited to very specific scenarios, since the browser still believes that it is interacting with the attacker's site, and therefore does not disclose third-party cookies or other sensitive information to the attacker.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Even when same-origin policy is in effect (without being relaxed by Cross-Origin Resource Sharing), certain cross-origin attacks can be performed.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] WebRTC can be used to find out the internal IP address of a victim.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] If attempting to connect to a cross-origin port, responses cannot be read in face of same-origin policy, but a JavaScript can still make inferences on whether the port is open or closed by checking if the onload/onerror event fires, or if we get a timeout.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] This gives opportunities for cross-origin portscanning.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Further, JavaScript snippets can use techniques like cross-site leaks to exploit long-standing information leakages in the browser to infer information cross-origin.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] These attacks can be counteracted by implementing a Cross-Origin Resource Policy (CORP) header, which allows a website owner to block cross-origin or cross-site resources, like images, videos, and stylesheets.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] CORP can also block JavaScript-initiated `fetch` requests, but only if they are sent with the `no-cors` request mode.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy does not prevent the browser from making GET, POST, OPTIONS, and TRACE requests; it only prevents the responses from being read by user code.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Therefore, if an endpoint uses one of these "safe" request methods to write information or perform an action on a user's behalf, it can be exploited by attackers.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Note that the same-origin policy does not apply to cookies for historical reasons.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] If multiple adversarial sites are deployed on the same hostname with different port numbers, contrary to the SOP, all cookies set by any of the sites are shared.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] This can be used to leak users' session tokens and steal account information.
[src:csp-hardening/same-origin-policy] Therefore, web services should be separated by differentiating subdomains rather than port numbers.
